/--
**Conjecture A6** (Quality: 0.76) — *Finite Maximal Associated Primes ⟹ Artinian*

Let R be a commutative Noetherian ring and M an R-module. If Ass_R(M) is
finite and every associated prime of M is maximal, then M is Artinian.

**Proof sketch.** If an R-module has finitely many associated primes and all
of them are maximal ideals, then the module is Artinian (satisfies the
descending chain condition on submodules). This generalizes the weakly
Artinian condition to full Artinian.

Source: STP.
-/
theorem artinian_of_finite_max_ass
    (R : Type*) [CommRing R] [IsNoetherianRing R]
    (M : Type*) [AddCommGroup M] [Module R M] [Module.Finite R M]
    (hFinAss : Set.Finite ((⊤ : Submodule R M).associatedPrimes))
    (hMaxAss : ∀ (p : Ideal R),
      p ∈ (⊤ : Submodule R M).associatedPrimes → p.IsMaximal) :
    IsArtinian R M := by
  sorry

/--
**Conjecture A7** (Quality: 0.75) — *Weakly Artinian iff Weakly Laskerian (Maximal Associated Primes)*

Let R be a commutative Noetherian ring and M a finitely generated R-module.
If Ass_R(M) is finite and consists entirely of maximal ideals, then M is
weakly Artinian if and only if M is weakly Laskerian.

**Proof sketch.** The forward direction follows from the definition. The
reverse uses the maximality of all associated primes to show that the
Laskerian condition (finitely many associated primes in every quotient)
implies the descending chain condition.

Source: STP.
-/
theorem weakly_artinian_iff_weakly_laskerian_of_max_ass
    (R : Type*) [CommRing R] [IsNoetherianRing R]
    (M : Type*) [AddCommGroup M] [Module R M] [Module.Finite R M]
    (hMaxAss : ∀ (p : Ideal R),
      p ∈ (⊤ : Submodule R M).associatedPrimes → p.IsMaximal) :
    -- Both directions: weakly Artinian ↔ weakly Laskerian
    -- Approximated as: Artinian (since Mathlib has no WeaklyArtinian/WeaklyLaskerian)
    IsArtinian R M := by
